latestPosts.caption:
December 2nd 2023 - I introduced myself as an INDIAN, they said you’re the winner @hipfestvn 

Sometimes I don’t dream, I just decide, I respect my decision and go out there to get it done no matter how long it takes! 

Last year December 2022 I made this decision to go out in 2023 and try your best to get India on top! But unfortunately I met with an accident later, that crushed me both physically and mentally, I was angry at myself for something which was not in my control (accident), I went through a surgery and had to rest for 3months - I used to be so annoyed at myself for this (not something I am proud of) 

A week after a surgery, I went to REDBULL dance your style but didn’t make it International, then came my another chance to rep india @battlerivalskool , I trained like no one else could even imagine, I sometimes used to feel sorry for myself for beating my body up so much for close to 7months

Went to my 2 international and lost in finals, I came back a little upset, 2 days later with no rest I went to @hipfestvn @indianhiphopnation qualifiers India, won both hip hop and all style, I decided then to give it another shot!

December 2nd 2023- It happened, winner of @hipfestvn 2023, one of the first jams for me to meet 15+ different countries best under one roof, all super talented and super different and you see that one Indian who comes from no where & takes India to the top of the table! INDIA said the crowd, waved hands, judges pointed towards me, all I could feel was silence in my soul, I did not feel excited/enthusiastic , I couldn’t jump, I did not even have a wide laugh, I just felt that silence/felt light as air- a small smile on my face, i sat down for a couple of seconds, I apologised to myself for beating myself though this whole year, I thanked my loved ones (you know who), my crew mates, my city, my indian community, my country and finally myself for making a decision and respecting it, lastly I got up saying ITS TIME FOR INDIA to be at the top just like today, it’s just the beginning! 

Thanks for all the love and support from all around the world! This is for all of us!

Repping 🇮🇳 @ftfwofficial @ownd.entity 

#respect

latestPosts.caption:
This was the first time in years that I reacted to a win with so much excitement. I couldn’t help but just dance around like a kid after I won. this win was personal, and this win was a process, 3 years of my journey and it all started here to get my hands on international trophies because I realised it was the need of the hour and I wanted Indian Street to make a mark on world stages! 

Allow me to take you through this, ( swipe through the posts )

The best from 3 years of Rivalskool experience and to see 🇮🇳 along with some of the best nations around the world- - - 
- first (🥇)- @candyman_badness ( Congo/Paris ),
- Second (🥈) - @dexterbravoorootz ( Senegal/ Paris ), 
- Third (🥉) - @pradeeeeep_____ ( INDIA ) - The Rivalskool Trilogy is complete, and I feel grateful and humbled. Last week was one of the most beautiful times. I will always remember it!

Thanks to @battlerivalskool for believing in me and appreciating this guy from India. Thanks to all the dancers and supporters who were part of this journey!

Representing India @ftfwofficial @ownd.entity - my people
Thanks to my loved ones who believe in me more than I believe in myself. You know who you are💙

Thanks to everyone who kept me motivated and sent sweet messages. Much love and appreciation for every effort because nothing is easy!

Lastly, Respect your thoughts and decisions, stay focused and disciplined, and make sure your life is the best story ever lived! 

Until next time, let’s keep dancing! 
I am heading back to training now because this is just the beginning! 

Thank you!

latestPosts.caption:
Surprised? But I wasn’t. When I won, I simply smiled—that says it all. I dance because it makes me live in the moment, and it shows the confidence I have in knowing how much I’ve worked for these moments—what it means to my crew, my loved ones, and my country🇮🇳. I came here well prepared, with only one intention: to enjoy dancing and share that joy with everyone watching me. For me, this is about more than just winning.

House dance and house music have been a secret love I took time to explore, and though I hardly competed in house in my own country I loved training this form from the time I started hip hop, but this time I went all out at Bad Vibes Battle ( @badvibes_battle ) in Thailand.
Sharing the stage with dancers from Thailand, Vietnam, Malaysia, France, Germany, the USA, Japan, China, Burma, and beyond was unforgettable. The energy, the music, and the talent pushed me to dance freely, share my roots, and connect with others. Hearing that I inspired people and gave them a fresh and new perspective reminds me of the importance of representing India with pride. This victory is for everyone back home who believed in me and celebrated this journey. Thank you for helping me bring a piece of India to the world stage again! As always this time it was mine and I always hope the next one is yours, art makes this world a better place so share your art with as many people as possible! 

Thanks to @joshije2 for making it to the top 6 and for all the meaningful conversations before and after the jam. It’s incredibly important to have the right company when competing at such a high level. We didn’t have any proper food, we lived on juice and buns, no drinks, no smokes, nor did we engage in any bad habits. Instead, we enjoyed great conversations about dance in general and representing our country. That connection is key to how passionately we represented!

1 vs 1 house winner 
1 vs 1 bounce rock and flow ( made it till top 6) 
Repping 🇮🇳 @ftfwofficial @ownd.entity 

This is my Christmas gift to y'all this year 🎁
.
.
.
.
PS : If you think it is easy - then everyone would do it! 
Mad respect to everyone who have put in the effort to represent Internationally 🫡

latestPosts.caption:
Yesterday was such a wholesome day!

I ended up winning both the 1v1 and 2v2 All Style battles—and the best part? I got to share the 2v2 win with an 11-year-old cutie who truly stole my heart.

Initially, I wasn’t even sure if I wanted to participate. I thought I’d just drop by and feel it out. But as I watched a bunch of kids take part in the same category, this one little girl mananya—she was dancing with such innocence, joy, and freedom. When she lost, I could see she was a little upset.

So I walked up to her, got down on one knee, and asked if she wanted to enter the 2v2 with me. She instantly lit up, hyped and excited. I promised her we’d win this for her no matter what—and in that moment, I wasn’t just dancing for myself, but for every kid who shows up fearlessly, who dances with heart and purity.

I wanted her to feel that joy of winning, of being seen and celebrated—something I never got to experience at her age or a kid. And we did it! The final video of her reaction is something I’ll treasure forever. That win was more than just a medal—it was a dream come true for her, and a healing moment for the inner child in me.

We don’t always need to be teachers or perfect dancers to inspire the next generation. Sometimes, just showing up, clapping for them, dancing beside them, and being present is enough. Your presence can plant a seed, create belonging, and give someone the courage to believe in themselves again.

As long as I can, I’ll keep showing up—not just for myself, but for anyone who looks up to me or wants to share a stage with me. Thank you to that little one (mananya🙍‍♀️)—for letting me relive my childhood through your spirit. She inspired me more than she knows.

Always greatful for this art form🕊
